{% extends "parts/base" %}
{%- block title -%}
	QuickStart
{%- endblock %}
{% block content %}

<p>You want to try our compiler? <span class="algo">Firm</span> in itself is just a library, so you probably want our C frontend cparser. Here is the fastest way to get it running.
</p><p><b>We assume a Linux or Mac OS X environment here.</b>
</p><p>Check it out with git:
</p>
{% code 'bash' %}
$ git clone http://pp.info.uni-karlsruhe.de/git/cparser.git
$ cd cparser
{% endcode %}
<p>If you want the latest stable release, instead of the current development version, checkout the latest tag:
</p>
{% code 'bash' %}
$ git checkout $(git describe --abbrev=0 --tags)
{% endcode %}
<p>Additionally, we need the <span class="algo">Firm</span> library, which is included as a submodule.
</p>
{% code 'bash' %}
$ git submodule update --init
{% endcode %}
<p>Now build everything. You need a C compiler, GNU Make, Perl, and Python.
</p>
{% code 'bash' %}
$ make
{% endcode %}
<p>You probably have a multicore machine? Then use something like <tt>make -j4</tt> for a parallel build.
</p><p>Now you should have a working binary.
</p>
{% code 'bash' %}
$ build/cparser --version
{% endcode %}
<p>Our compiler tries to be a drop in replacement for GCC, so it supports the same arguments.
Try it on some C99 code, like <tt>cparser -Wall -O3 test.c</tt> or <tt>make CC=cparser</tt>.
</p><p>If you find bugs, please report them in our <a class="external text" href="http://pp.info.uni-karlsruhe.de/~firm/bugs/">issue tracker</a>.
</p>
{% endblock %}
